arch:property.oc:show_val: Dry sieve. This is a large midden unit. It overwhelmingly consists of sheep-size animals, although cattle-size, pig-size, and hare-size also exist (see taxa representation below). Surface condition is moderate on average, some really quite fresh and majority moderate, and not many degraded ones; perhaps there were variable accumulation rates. There is little burning (1-2%); low temperature. Fair amount of digestion, low percentage, but significant. There is little gnawing; a fair amount of delicate pieces, such as proximal humerus, have survived which indicates dogs have not gone through the bones. Most pieces are highly fragmented, some are moderately fragmented. Fragment size ranges between 2-20 cm, averaging to about 4-7 cm range. Mostly old (predepositional) breaks. Half of the unit is diagnostics, (in terms of volume, but not in numbers). Diagnostics are overwhelmingly sheep/goat. Other taxa in the diagnostics are: cattle, equid (two teeth), boar (several teeth, some of which are suggestive of youth), dog, fox, bird, any other? (add range of elements for all these taxa!). Cattle: phalanx, cranial). There are also two large fragments of human bone (mature ulna and tibia). Human bones (that are found in burials) usually look much less compact and dense than the animal bones. However, these two human bones seem very similar to animal bones in terms of bone structure; they are much less frail. Therefore, these human bones may not be from burials and/or they may not have been buried with the flesh on. All body parts are present for the sheep-size. Compared to the other middens, an unusually large amount of ribs and vertebrae are present. However, we’ve been getting this kind of body-part distribution in the Level IV middens, and these may be typical for Level IV. There is an unusually small number of bone tools, and these are fragmented. This deposit seems like a single-purpose midden: very focused, virtually all related to consumption discard; very few other activities. Again, this is in contrast to what we get in the usual middens which are more mixed, coming from consumption as well as other activities. This midden was partially dug in 2007 by Ruth (3 out of 4 layers of midden dug are in phase with what Ruth was digging). This unit 16253 (this unit) is similar to those units of the midden from last year (unit numbers? Check online priority). Flotation sample >4mm, 100% sorted, Flot # 7830. A smallish flotation sample given the size of the unit, with a few cattle-sized pieces of scrap but otherwise all caprine-sized animals. All diagnostics are caprine; a full range of body parts. Some digestion, but not very much-- far, far less than, say, 16262 from the same midden sequence. Very little burning (ca 2%), only to carbonization at most. Surface conditions moderate-- nothing looks really fresh, and nothing looks really rolled. On the whole, the flotation sample looks a lot like the rest of the unit.
Arzu Demirergi, Katheryn Twiss, David Orton
